<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1924-12-01T23:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1924-12-01T23:00:00-05:00" n="371" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d371">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/5805: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Mayer</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1924-12-02T12:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">December 2,
                                        1924—noon</hi></date>.<lb/>[Received December 2—3:33
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>466. My number 465, December 1, 4 p.m. Chang Tso-lin without warning left
                            Peking December 2, 4 a.m., I am informed, for Tientsin taking
                            headquarters staff and bodyguard. Sun Fo and other Kuomintang leaders in
                            Peking.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Mayer</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>